riant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Guillaume de Saint-Aubyn II was born about 1097, in Devon, England, United Kingdom as the son of Mauger de Saint-Aubyn I. He had at least 1 son. He died about 1152, in Crediton, Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 57."},"et":{"Abt 1097–Abt 1152":"umbes 1097–umbes 1152","1097–1152":"1097–1152","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1070–1122":"1070–1122","Abt 1097":"umbes 1097","Abt 1152":"umbes 1152","Abt 1122":"umbes 1122","1122":"1122","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","1097":"1097","1070":"1070","prob., Crediton, Devon, England":"Crediton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1097–Abt 1152":"noin 1097–noin 1152","1097–1152":"1097–1152","1130–Male":"1130–Kuollut","1070–1122":"1070–1122","Abt 1097":"noin 1097","Abt 1152":"noin 1152","Abt 1122":"noin 1122","1122":"1122","1130":"1130","1152":"1152","1097":"1097","1070":"1070","prob., Crediton, Devon, England":"Credito